WHAT IS THIS KINGDOM
The domain that defines the capture, reconstruction, and
representation of three-dimensional and immersive visual content
beyond the traditional 2D frame. It encompasses MPEG Immersive
Media standards (MPEG-I Visual), volumetric video capture and
compression, 3D Gaussian Splatting for dynamic scene reconstruction,
physics-aware volumetric reconstruction (PAVR), light-field
capture systems, and point cloud processing pipelines. It is the
layer that enables a scene to be captured once and experienced
from any viewpoint, on any display, with full parallax and
preserved lighting fidelity.

WHY IT EXISTS
The future of visual storytelling is not a fixed rectangle. From
virtual production on LED volumes to Apple Vision Pro immersive
video, the industry needs a protocol that handles three-dimensional
scene data with the same rigor that GIOP brings to 2D imagery.
This kingdom ensures that volumetric content is color-accurate,
temporally coherent, physically plausible, and interoperable
across all viewing platforms.

HOW IT IS STRUCTURED
Six sub-domains: MPEG Immersive Media and 6DoF Standards,
Volumetric Video Pipelines, 3D Gaussian Splatting for Dynamic
Captures, Physics-Aware Volumetric Reconstruction (PAVR),
Light-Field Capture and Rendering, and Point Cloud Processing
and Compression. Each section defines the mathematical models,
file formats, and quality constraints.

WHERE IT IS APPLIED
Virtual production stages, volumetric capture studios, sports
broadcast (multi-view replay), immersive filmmaking (Apple
Immersive Video), cultural heritage digitization, telepresence
and holoportation, and next-generation spatial computing
applications.

WHO USES IT
Volumetric capture engineers, VFX supervisors, immersive
experience designers, and pipeline architects building the next
generation of 3D media.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Replaces proprietary volumetric formats with a single, open,
GIOP-based representation that preserves the full color pipeline.
Ensures that a volumetric capture matches the look of the
corresponding 2D camera captures within ACES. Defines quality
metrics for geometric accuracy and view-dependent color fidelity.

1. MPEG IMMERSIVE MEDIA AND 6DOF STANDARDS
MPEG-I (ISO/IEC 23090) is the first international standard for
immersive media, targeting 6 degrees of freedom (6DoF) viewing.

MPEG-I Visual (Part 12): defines a bitstream format that supports
view-dependent streaming of immersive video. The scene is
represented as a combination of:
  - A geometric model (mesh or point cloud).
  - Atlas data: patches of texture packed into video streams.
  - Metadata: camera parameters, depth maps, and rendering hints.

The viewer position and orientation determine which patches
are streamed at what resolution, similar to adaptive bitrate
streaming for 2D video.

GIOP defines the color pipeline within MPEG-I:
  - Textures are encoded in ACES2065-1 linear or ACEScct log.
  - The AMF (Kingdom 09) is embedded per atlas, specifying the
    IDT of the capture cameras, any LMTs applied, and the
    mastering display ODT if pre-rendered for a specific display.
  - The geometric model is in scene-linear units, with the
    reflectance (albedo) separated from the incident illumination
    using intrinsic decomposition. This enables relighting of
    the captured scene.

6DoF audio: MPEG-I Audio (Part 4) provides object-based and
scene-based audio that responds to listener position. GIOP
synchronizes audio and visual metadata via SMPTE timecode.

2. VOLUMETRIC VIDEO PIPELINES
A volumetric video pipeline captures a dynamic 3D scene, typically
using an array of synchronized cameras, and reconstructs a
time-varying 3D representation.

Capture: a dome or cylinder of cameras (typ. 16 to 100+ cameras,
global shutter, genlocked) captures the scene from all angles.
Cameras are calibrated geometrically (intrinsics, extrinsics) and
colorimetrically (per-camera IDT to ACES2065-1). GIOP mandates
that the calibration data for every camera be stored as a
certified GIOP Body profile.

Reconstruction: Multi-View Stereo (MVS) and depth map fusion
produce a dense 3D mesh or point cloud. The mesh is textured
using the camera images, with per-vertex or per-texel color
in ACES2065-1. Intrinsic decomposition separates albedo and
shading under the capture illumination.

Post-production: the volumetric sequence is edited, graded,
and optionally relit. GIOP-compliant volumetric tools allow
the colorist to apply looks in ACEScct to a reference viewpoint;
the look is then propagated to all viewpoints via the scene's
geometric and reflectance representation, ensuring consistent
color across all viewing angles.

Compression and delivery: the volumetric video is compressed
using MPEG-I Visual, 3D Gaussian Splatting (Section 3), or
a point cloud codec (Section 6). The compressed bitstream
carries the full ACES color pipeline metadata.

3. 3D GAUSSIAN SPLATTING FOR DYNAMIC CAPTURES
3D Gaussian Splatting (3DGS, see Kingdom 07 Section 2) is
extended to dynamic (4D) captures for real-time novel view
synthesis.

A dynamic scene is represented as a collection of 3D Gaussians
with time-varying parameters: position mu(t), covariance Sigma(t),
opacity o(t), and SH coefficients for color c(t). The temporal
evolution is modeled either by:
  - Per-Gaussian learned trajectories (polynomials or splines).
  - A deformation field: a neural network predicts the offset
    from a canonical pose: delta_mu = MLP(mu_canonical, t).

Training objectives for dynamic scenes:
  - L1 and D-SSIM loss on all training views and time instants.
  - Temporal consistency loss: penalize large changes in Gaussian
    parameters between adjacent frames, weighted by the magnitude
    of scene motion (derived from 2D optical flow or 3D scene flow).
  - Flow alignment loss (Edge4DGS, MotionScale 2025): the 3D
    motion of each Gaussian center, projected to 2D, must match
    the observed optical flow.

GIOP defines a standard container for a 4DGS asset:
  - The canonical Gaussians and the deformation model weights.
  - The ACES2065-1 color space for the SH coefficients.
  - A reference camera rig (positions, orientations) that matches
    the capture array, allowing GIOP to query any novel view with
    the same camera model as physical cameras.

Quality metrics for dynamic 3DGS:
  - PSNR, SSIM, and LPIPS evaluated on held-out views.
  - Temporal flicker index: standard deviation of pixel values of
    a static region over time, must be below JND threshold.
  - Color accuracy: CIEDE2000 on a ColorChecker placed in the scene,
    compared to ground-truth captures, must average below 2.0.

4. PHYSICS-AWARE VOLUMETRIC RECONSTRUCTION (PAVR)
PAVR frameworks reconstruct not just the visual appearance but
the underlying physical properties of a scene, enabling physically
plausible relighting and material editing.

Input: calibrated multi-view images under controlled or known
illumination.

Output:
  - Per-point or per-surface-patch albedo (diffuse reflectance).
  - Surface normals.
  - Specular parameters (roughness, F0).
  - An environment map of the capture illumination.

The forward rendering model:
  Rendered_color = albedo * (N·L) * diffuse_lighting +
                   specular_BRDF(roughness, F0) * specular_lighting +
                   ambient

Reconstruction loss: photometric error between rendered and
captured images, summed over all viewpoints and illumination
conditions if available.

GIOP integration:
  - The reconstructed albedo is stored in ACES2065-1.
  - The illumination is stored as an HDR environment map
    (linear radiance, ACES2065-1) and as a GIOP-certified
    light source profile.
  - Relighting is performed by replacing the environment map
    and re-rendering. The result remains in the ACES pipeline
    and is directly comparable to 2D camera footage shot under
    the new lighting.

PAVR is the preferred workflow for virtual production, where
captured actors must be seamlessly lit by the LED volume's
virtual environment.

5. LIGHT-FIELD CAPTURE AND RENDERING
A light-field camera captures the radiance along rays passing
through a plane or volume, enabling post-capture refocus and
parallax.

Plenoptic function (Adelson & Bergen, 7D):
  L(x, y, z, theta, phi, lambda, t)
Practical light-field cameras sample a 4D subset (x, y, u, v),
where (x,y) is the spatial coordinate and (u,v) is the angular
coordinate.

Micro-lens array based light-field camera (e.g., Lytro, Raytrix):
  d = (f_MLA * b) / (b - f_MLA)
where d is the distance from the micro-lens array to the sensor,
f_MLA is the focal length of each micro-lens, and b is the distance
from the main lens to the micro-lens array.

Light-field processing in GIOP:
  - Raw light-field images are linearized using the camera's IDT.
  - Depth maps are extracted from the 4D data using defocus
    correspondence or phase-based methods.
  - The light-field can be rendered to any virtual aperture,
    focus distance, and depth of field, with all rendering
    occurring in ACEScct or ACEScg to maintain color fidelity.
  - The light-field file (.lfr) includes per-ray color
    in ACES2065-1, depth, and confidence. GIOP defines the
    .lfr container as an open format.

Applications: visual effects (re-focus without re-shooting),
depth-based compositing, and virtual cinematography where the
camera's focus and iris are animated in post.

6. POINT CLOUD PROCESSING AND COMPRESSION
Point clouds are an alternative volumetric representation,
particularly for real-time applications.

Geometry: a set of 3D points (x, y, z), optionally with color
(R,G,B or Y,Cb,Cr), normals, and reflectance.

Compression standards:
  - V-PCC (Video-based Point Cloud Compression, MPEG): projects
    the point cloud onto 2D patches, encodes the patches as a
    video stream (HEVC or VVC), and encodes the geometry as a
    supplementary depth video. Achieves high compression ratios.
  - G-PCC (Geometry-based Point Cloud Compression, MPEG): encodes
    the point cloud directly using octree decomposition and
    attribute prediction. Suitable for sparse, non-surface-like
    point clouds (e.g., LiDAR).

GIOP color encoding: point cloud attributes (color, reflectance)
must be encoded in a GIOP-defined log space (ACEScct recommended)
to match the perceptual uniformity of the rest of the pipeline.
For V-PCC, the 2D patches are encoded with GIOP codec-aware
color management (Kingdom 08 Section 7). For G-PCC, the attribute
prediction residual is compressed losslessly or with visually
lossless quantization defined by an ITU-R BT.2124-based model.

Point cloud quality metrics:
  - Geometric error: point-to-point (D1) and point-to-plane (D2)
    Hausdorff distances.
  - Color error: CIEDE2000 between the compressed and original
    colors, evaluated on a reference rendering of the point cloud
    from a set of standard viewpoints.

